  <section class="faq-section"><div class="container">
    <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><p>Common questions about lifetime free credit cards</p></div>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Is lifetime free really free forever?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes, a genuine lifetime free (LTF) credit card has zero joining fee and zero annual fee for the entire duration you hold the card — there are no hidden conditions or minimum spending requirements. However, be cautious of cards marketed as "first year free" or "free with annual spend waiver" — these are not truly LTF. Always verify in the card's terms and conditions that it explicitly states "lifetime free" or "no annual/renewal fee applicable." Cards like ICICI Amazon Pay, Axis ACE, and IDFC First WOW are confirmed lifetime free without any conditions.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Can I get a premium card for free?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">While super-premium cards like HDFC Infinia or Diners Black aren't available as LTF, several mid-premium cards offer impressive perks for free. The IDFC First WOW card includes zero forex markup and 4 lounge visits per year — features usually found only in paid cards. The AU Lit Card offers complimentary lounge access, insurance benefits, and solid rewards at zero cost. These cards bridge the gap between basic free cards and expensive premium cards, giving you 70-80% of premium benefits at zero annual fee.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Do lifetime free cards have lower credit limits?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Not necessarily. Credit limits are determined by your income, credit score, and relationship with the bank — not by whether the card is free or paid. Many LTF cardholders with a good CIBIL score (750+) and stable income receive limits of ₹2-5 lakh. However, the initial limit on an LTF card may be slightly lower than a premium paid card. You can request a limit increase after 6-12 months of responsible usage and timely payments. Most banks automatically review and increase limits periodically for well-managed accounts.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Which is the best lifetime free card for first-time users?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">For first-time credit card users, we recommend the ICICI Amazon Pay card or IndusInd Tiger card. The Amazon Pay card is ideal if you shop on Amazon regularly (5% cashback for Prime members) and has easy approval criteria. The IndusInd Tiger card is better if you want simple, universal cashback (1.5% on everything) without worrying about categories. Both cards have zero fees, help build your credit history, and are easy to get approved for with minimal income requirements. Start with one of these, use it responsibly for 6-12 months, then consider upgrading to a premium card.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Can the bank start charging fees on my LTF card later?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Banks are contractually bound by the terms under which you were issued the card. If your card was issued as "lifetime free," the bank cannot unilaterally start charging annual fees. However, banks can: (1) Discontinue the card variant and offer to migrate you to a different card (which may have fees), (2) Change reward structures or benefits while keeping the card free. If a bank contacts you about a migration, you have the right to refuse and retain your LTF card or close it without penalty. Always save your original card terms document as proof.</div></div></div>
    </div>
  </div></section>

